<!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://www.garfield.com"><!--EZCODE IMAGE START--><img src="http://members.cox.net/impudent/strip3.jpg" style="border:0;"/><!--EZCODE IMAGE END--></a><!--EZCODE LINK END--></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#000000><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub54.ezboard.com/bquelliousquaterstherebirth.showUserPublicProfile?gid=valdayana>Valdayana</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Ruler of Quellious</span><br>  Posts: 74<br> <font color=#00CCFF>(12/6/02 4:30:57 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub54.ezboard.com/fquelliousquaterstherebirthfrm13.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=725.topic&index=2>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Loot rules</span><hr size=1> The best system is one that gives everyone input, where people can be expected to be honest on their desire for whatever item it is and understanding enough to know that if they recently got something they shouldn't ask for another thing.. having a system like that is fair and ensures that people get the items they really want, assuming everyone's honest.  You know the system is working when once an item drops, everyone says &quot;you know, this item is meant for soandso, lets give it to him/her&quot;, or you have 5 or 6 people who it's an upgrade for pass on it because they know the 7th person hasn't received anything for a while.  Of course, what kind of guild would be able to use such a system?  Probably a bunch of nerds.. and certainly no one uber. *Looks innocent*<br>
<br>
Valdayana D'Varr <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#000000><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub54.ezboard.com/bquelliousquaterstherebirth.showUserPublicProfile?gid=bippity>Bippity</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Sebilite Golem</span><br>  Posts: 71<br> <font color=#00CCFF>(12/6/02 4:40:45 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub54.ezboard.com/fquelliousquaterstherebirthfrm13.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=725.topic&index=3>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Lewt Rules?</span><hr size=1> Points Pros - Non-subjective, easily tracked, loot goes to the people who raid the most, few arguements about who gets what.<br>
<br>
Points Cons - Person with highest points might not be best to get items, can get DKP(oint) whores who save up and buy best stuff only, harse for people who dont play alot, alot of bookeeping. Doesnt really work unless you raid frequently.<br>
<br>
<br>
Subjective/Loot Council Pro - Officers can choose best path of upgrades for people, easier to work with since less set rules, easier on people who cant raid as much<br>
<br>
Sub/Council Con - People quick to jump on 'favoritism', somewhat hard to keep track of everyone's progress and such, lotsa stress on people who decide loot; person(s) who hand out loot need to know what they are doing.<br>
<br>
Random Pro - equal to all people regardless of how much they raid, best for people who dont raid much, noone complains about where loot goes.<br>
<br>
Random Con - Everyone has same chance to win regardless of how much they raid, loot given out sporadically, no control over loot, people who raid alot generally dont like it when people who never raid win stuff :)<br>
<br>
<br>
Most starting guilds or 'family/friends' guilds go random, though, if/when you want to move up to more raid oriented stuff, people will be used to the randoming and wont want to change to a point or subjective system.  Subjective loot is prolly better if you are going to keep membership kinda low like 30-40ish people.  Some people do a combination of points and random in that the points affect what they random, so the people who dont raid get a shot, but the people who do raid get a better shot.  It all depends on what you plan on doing with the guild mainly, and what kind of people you have. <p><!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=5794">Bippity</a><!--EZCODE LINK END--> Hierophant / <!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=27969">Gobbo</a><!--EZCODE LINK END--> Warlord<br>
Quellious<br>
</p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#000000><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub54.ezboard.com/bquelliousquaterstherebirth.showUserPublicProfile?gid=cyllyan>Cyllyan</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Duracyl the mana battery</span><br>  Posts: 217<br> <font color=#00CCFF>(12/6/02 7:06:35 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub54.ezboard.com/fquelliousquaterstherebirthfrm13.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=725.topic&index=4>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Lewt Rules?</span><hr size=1> Fallen Eagles went with a point system a while ago, and it's actually worked out pretty well for what is pretty much a mid-to-high-level raiding/family &amp; friends guild.<br>
<br>
We did however have to put in a rule where new people could not roll on anything until they had attended 7 raids, (or a 350+ bonus towards a roll - 50 points accrue for each raid attended.) The reason we had to do this is we were experiencing a lot of &quot;loot-n-scoot&quot; where people would win big phat lewtz and then disband from the guild. <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :bad --><img src=http://www.quellious-collective.com/emoticons/bad.gif ALT=":bad"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->   to those people. <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://216.40.249.192/mysmilies/contrib/guus/tong.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->  <br>
<br>
Good luck on your new guild, Lae! I hope things work out well for you.<br>
<br>
Cyllyan<br>
54th fruitybard of Fallen Eagles<br>
 <p></p><i>Edited by: <A HREF=http://pub54.ezboard.com/bquelliousquaterstherebirth.showUserPublicProfile?gid=cyllyan>Cyllyan</A> at: 12/6/02 7:15:06 pm<br></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#000000><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub54.ezboard.com/bquelliousquaterstherebirth.showUserPublicProfile?gid=laeena>Laeena</A>&nbsp; <IMG HEIGHT=10 WIDTH=10 SRC="http://www.tinkering.org/ezboard/dance.gif" BORDER=0></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Froglok Krup Shaman</span><br>  Posts: 43<br> <font color=#00CCFF>(12/6/02 7:08:54 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub54.ezboard.com/fquelliousquaterstherebirthfrm13.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=725.topic&index=5>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Lewt Rules?</span><hr size=1> At the moment we have about 15 members. 80% of the guild has toons who are 50+. Right now we are just putting things together and haven't started a formal hunting schedule. As time passes we are hoping to raid (50+) at a minimum of twice a week and have 2 low level (mid 30's to 40's) events a month. <br>
<br>
Like you said, people don't like a change in policy once they are accustom to things so we are hoping to establish an official loot rule to put into place before we invite more people. <br>
<br>
We probably won't use anything other then 'can and will' until we are larger, but I want to be up front with potential members as they are joining that things are changing soon and what they can expect.<br>
<br>
Of course, in a perfect world, items would default to the person most in need or to the person who never wins. For the most part, that was the way it was in my old guild. Everyone was pretty fair. I am hoping for the same here, but I want to be fair to the other officers and keep an open mind.<br>
<br>
Another loot cue I was thinking of is 'can and will use' /ran 100 +5 for each level above 50. That way the higher level toons will have a slightly better chance at getting an uber item. For instance a lvl 53 toon would /ran 115 on the item they desired. <br>
<br>
Thanks for the info so far, it makes it so much easier to present to the other officers in a fair way when I understand the positive and negatives for each way of handling loots.<br>
<br>
Lae <p><marquee bgcolor=#fffc17><font face=’veranda’ color=#000000>Magelo profiles coming soon to a MB near you!</font></marquee><br><br>
